</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DC05C38A09D38929ABA4455BDD433313" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="holotype">
<paragraph id="4A014F1A845B3132B925FC6FEFCE4160" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Holotype</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5CF3FEA640668046347D3B8A40A6D03D" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">(ZMH 79369):Shell height 8.0 mm, width 5.0 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2EFA4FB6F0871E137F4DCEE38A715620" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="D7517EF3AB349A9748BCB323658E1D72" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="10E50AB122F546A4B72E8D0E0938BF33" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Named after the region where the species was collected.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CF97C44DD53ADCFD143D985B80DE5E54" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph id="D57F49E7CB9199A3719FB5DBAB994112" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="55F9A93B8148B6323DAF5C7475E612B6" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">The horn-coloured shell is conical with 5.5 whorls, which are slightly convex with a clear suture and an acute apex. The umbilicus is closed. The aperture is ovate, angled at the top. The margin of the aperture is, from lateral view, sinuated. The surface bears a lattice structure. Shell height 8.0 mm, width 5.0 mm, aperture height 3.6 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F85B7BBCFDB1835D06C3737FDFFC2D87" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="differentiating features">
<paragraph id="18990316399880EEBC9188808D6BC9DA" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Differentiating features.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F838ACC574A0E6DC9742655FCCD9D48C" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">
The new species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="095E7C234ECCF2E29ED5DBDB96B33A4C" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Gastropoda" family="Bithyniidae" genus="Bithynia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tentaculata">
<emphasis id="AE47EA70358F0B586BF5C79341117C42" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Bithynia tentaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs from it by the following features: (i) the operculum is more angled (
<figureCitation id="42B820A8669320CB13082D78FC32390E" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Bithynia mazandaranensis sp. n. a, b shell c operculum d detail of the shell surface." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/20809" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7c</figureCitation>
), (ii) the whorls are more convex (
<figureCitation id="55FD1F9130976FB6710CEB1664017F2D" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Bithynia mazandaranensis sp. n. a, b shell c operculum d detail of the shell surface." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/20809" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7a-b</figureCitation>
), and (iii) the surface has longitudinal and transverse striae (
<figureCitation id="0D4C47B5BD1B52F3DC5BBEC6F30E33FD" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Bithynia mazandaranensis sp. n. a, b shell c operculum d detail of the shell surface." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/20809" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5592CC2DFFCD62D0B959F9B05FF1A6F1" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="associated species">
<paragraph id="3B51E124F6CD7F3B74F17F7A716780F1" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Associated species.</paragraph>
